<br>
Barry Spatz, <br>
look at John's post, I'm saying let's play football no matter what the odds are agaisnt us. Let's face the real issues that we faced in Nam and exaime them for what they were.<br><br>
 What Ive said is simple and even gave you and others a simple illustration of knowing what the odds are. John wrote that the odds were stacked against us in Nam. We now know that and much more. <br><br>
Still what I'. saying is that the politicans, communist and social do gooders were not our teachers.<br>
We played their game according to the rules and regulations our political leaders dealt us. We played against a cheating, deceiving, untrustworthy but formable foe.<br><br>
And you know what? What John did not say is that we won. We won almost every scrimmage we played and kept moving the football to the other edges of the field and came close to the goal line and scoring often, but it was then our president called time out and this gave the enemy time to regroup and get resupplied. We were not suppose to fire on them during the cease fire holidays (theirs and ours) but they often chose to do so, without reservation. When it was necessary we even went after the football outside the bounds of the playing field (Laos/Cambodia) knowing that ever if we scored outside the supposedly playing field it was going to count against us, still we played football under those conditions and we kept winning the battles in Nam in spit of the protests, unsupported, lack of equipment and even though often the enemy knew where we were going to be before we got there. Heck we often announced it to them overhead by low flying boombox bombers that dropped leaflets and told the enemy over loud spaeakers that we were coming. <br>
What I'm saying is simple, we don't need to compare fish, or the size of the catch to prove who's the better fishermen.<br>
I've never been in competition with you. I have shared with you and others what I experienced, what I did, what I believed and why I fought in Nam. I've shared with you and others the fears I've faced and had to deal with and I've asked nothing from you.<br><br>
It's when you post one thing and proclaim another that bothers me. Flip-floping to gain acceptance is not necessary. We've accepted who you are. tell us that. Not what you think we want to hear.<br><br>
Like Randy Caudill the Marine arrested recently for desertion after 30 years of living in Canada (today's LA Times). If he says he was just plain scared which the evidence stacked against him has already reflected, and in the statements others have said he told them, I have no problem with that. <br>
Cut him loose, no need to punish the coward. I can understand his fear, he may not like the name he has had to lived with all his life but he choose that road to travel. Its not a nice word or probably politically correct in today's society. But it's the truth that described that he lacked courage to go to Nam. Forgive him, that's no problem, but that does not change things or what he did.<br>
If he begins to play the political field, saying our country was wrong and so he decided to protest by going to Canada then I say Hang him. The individual fled from doing his duty because he was scared but kept crossing the border back and forth to take advantage of what goods the US had to offer. <br><br>
Next time you see a bum &quot;on the freeway on ramps saying &quot;agent orange-viet viet-will work for food,&quot; take the time to stop, get out and talk to him for awhile, you may just find out that he was never there in Nam, or perhaps even in the military. That he's a fake. I've yet to find a real vet asking for such donations. Yesterday in front of WalMart I found an individual sasking to help Homeless Vietnam Vets. But he had no connections with such individuals, he was collecting for his church and not Viet vets. But, the public will only see the &quot;Homeless Vietvet, and toss in another coin and apease their conscience for another season.<br><br>

